[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-credentials] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-credentials] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-credentials] The HTTP **`Access-Control-Allow-Credentials`** response header tells browsers whether the server allows credentials to be included in cross-origin HTTP requests.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-credentials] Credentials include cookies, Transport Layer Security (TLS) client certificates, or authentication headers containing a username and password.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-credentials] By default, these credentials are not sent in cross-origin requests, and doing so can make a site vulnerable to Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-credentials] The server allows credentials to be included in cross-origin HTTP requests.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-credentials] This is the only valid value for this header and is case-sensitive.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-credentials] If you don't need credentials, omit this header entirely rather than setting its value to `false`.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-origin] The HTTP **`Access-Control-Allow-Origin`** response header indicates whether the response can be shared with requesting code from the given origin.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-origin] The requesting code from any origin is allowed to access the resource.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-origin] For requests *without credentials*, the literal value `*` can be specified as a wildcard.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-origin] Attempting to use the wildcard with credentials results in an error.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-origin] If the server supports clients from multiple origins, it must return the origin for the specific client making the request.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-origin] Suppose the server sends a response with an `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` value with an explicit origin (rather than the `*` wildcard).
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/access-control-allow-origin] In that case, the response should also include a `Vary` response header with the value `Origin` — to indicate to browsers that server responses can differ based on the value of the `Origin` request header.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) is a standard that allows a server to relax the same-origin policy.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] This is used to explicitly allow some cross-origin requests while rejecting others.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] For example, if a site offers an embeddable service, it may be necessary to relax certain restrictions.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] Setting up such a CORS configuration isn't necessarily easy and may present some challenges.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] In these pages, we'll look into some common CORS error messages and how to resolve them.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] If the CORS configuration isn't set up correctly, the browser console will present an error like `"Cross-Origin Request Blocked: The Same Origin Policy disallows reading the remote resource at [some site]"` indicating that the request was blocked due to violating the CORS security rules.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] This might not necessarily be a set-up mistake, though.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] It's possible that the request is in fact intentionally being disallowed by the user's web application and remote external service.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] However, if the endpoint is meant to be available, some debugging is needed to succeed.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] To understand the underlying issue with the CORS configuration, you need to find out which request is at fault and why.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] Now try to reproduce the failing transaction and check the console if you are seeing a CORS violation error message.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] Most CORS errors can only be resolved on the server, because the server controls whether cross-origin access is allowed.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] Browsers send a preflight request before the actual request when certain conditions are met (custom headers, methods other than `GET`/`HEAD`/`POST`, or non-simple content types).
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] Simple requests bypass the preflight step entirely, which avoids a class of CORS errors related to preflight handling.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] The response will be opaque: its status is `0`, its headers are empty, and its body is not readable by JavaScript.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] This is by design - `no-cors` disables the CORS check, but in exchange you lose all access to the response content.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] If you do not control the remote server and it does not set CORS headers, you can route requests through a server you do control.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] Your server fetches the resource on your behalf and returns it with appropriate CORS headers.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] This approach adds latency and introduces a dependency on your proxy, but it works when other options are unavailable.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] Firefox's console displays messages in its console when requests fail due to CORS.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] Part of the error text is a "reason" message that provides added insight into what went wrong.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] The reason messages are listed below; click the message to open an article explaining the error in more detail and offering possible solutions.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cors-errors] This is by design — `no-cors` disables the CORS check, but in exchange you lose all access to the response content.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] In computing, **cross-origin resource sharing** (**CORS**) is a mechanism to safely bypass the same-origin policy; that is, it allows a web page to access restricted resources from a web server on a domain name different from the domain that served the web page.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A web page may freely embed cross-origin images, stylesheets, scripts, iframes, and videos.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Certain "cross-domain" HTTP requests, notably Ajax requests, are forbidden by default by the same-origin security policy.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] CORS defines a way in which a web browser and server can interact to determine whether it is safe to allow the cross-origin request.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] It allows for more freedom and functionality than purely same-origin requests, but is more secure than simply allowing all cross-origin requests.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The specification for CORS is included as part of the WHATWG's Fetch Living Standard.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] This specification describes how CORS is currently implemented in browsers.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] An earlier specification was published as a W3C Recommendation.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Servers can also notify clients whether "credentials" (including Cookies and HTTP Authentication data) should be sent with requests.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Suppose a user visits http://www.example.com and the page attempts a cross-origin request to fetch data from http://service.example.com.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A CORS-compatible browser will attempt to make a cross-origin request to service.example.com as follows.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A wildcard same-origin policy is appropriate when a page or API response is intended to be accessible to any code on any site.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] A freely available web font on a public hosting service like Google Fonts is an example.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The value of "*" is special in that it does not allow requests to supply credentials, meaning that it does not allow HTTP authentication, client-side SSL certificates, or cookies to be sent in the cross-domain request.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Note that in the CORS architecture, the Access-Control-Allow-Origin header is being set by the external web service (*service.example.com*), not the original web application server (*www.example.com*).
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Here, *service.example.com* uses CORS to permit the browser to authorize *www.example.com* to make requests to *service.example.com*.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] If a site specifies the header "Access-Control-Allow-Credentials:true", third-party sites may be able to carry out privileged actions and retrieve sensitive information.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] When performing certain types of cross-domain Ajax requests, modern browsers that support CORS will initiate an extra "preflight" request to determine whether they have permission to perform the action.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Cross-origin requests are preflighted this way because they may have implications to user data.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The browser will then make the actual request.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] If service.example.com does not accept cross-site requests from this origin then it will respond with error to the OPTIONS request and the browser will not make the actual request.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] Cross-origin support was originally proposed by Matt Oshry, Brad Porter, and Michael Bodell of Tellme Networks in March 2004 for inclusion in VoiceXML 2.1 to allow safe cross-origin data requests by VoiceXML browsers.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The mechanism was deemed general in nature and not specific to VoiceXML and was subsequently separated into an implementation NOTE.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The WebApps Working Group of the W3C with participation from the major browser vendors began to formalize the NOTE into a W3C Working Draft on track toward formal W3C Recommendation status.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] In May 2006 the first W3C Working Draft was submitted.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] In March 2009 the draft was renamed to "Cross-Origin Resource Sharing" and in January 2014 it was accepted as a W3C Recommendation.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] The main advantage of JSONP was its ability to work on legacy browsers which predate CORS support (Opera Mini and Internet Explorer 9 and earlier).
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/cross-origin-resource-sharing] CORS is now supported by most modern web browsers, and can be used as a modern alternative to the JSONP pattern.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] An example of a cross-origin request: the front-end JavaScript code served from `https://domain-a.com` uses `fetch()` to make a request for `https://domain-b.com/data.json`.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] For security reasons, browsers restrict cross-origin HTTP requests initiated from scripts.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] For example, `fetch()` and `XMLHttpRequest` follow the same-origin policy.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] This means that a web application using those APIs can only request resources from the same origin the application was loaded from unless the response from other origins includes the right CORS headers.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The CORS mechanism supports secure cross-origin requests and data transfers between browsers and servers.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Browsers use CORS in APIs such as `fetch()` or `XMLHttpRequest` to mitigate the risks of cross-origin HTTP requests.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] This is a general article about Cross-Origin Resource Sharing and includes a discussion of the necessary HTTP headers.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The Cross-Origin Resource Sharing standard works by adding new HTTP headers that let servers describe which origins are permitted to read that information from a web browser.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Servers can also inform clients whether "credentials" (such as Cookies and HTTP Authentication) should be sent with requests.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] CORS failures result in errors but for security reasons, specifics about the error *are not available to JavaScript*.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] All the code knows is that an error occurred.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The only way to determine what specifically went wrong is to look at the browser's console for details.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Subsequent sections discuss scenarios, as well as provide a breakdown of the HTTP headers used.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] We present three scenarios that demonstrate how Cross-Origin Resource Sharing works.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] All these examples use `fetch()`, which can make cross-origin requests in any supporting browser.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Some requests don't trigger a CORS preflight.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Those are called *simple requests* from the obsolete CORS spec, though the Fetch spec (which now defines CORS) doesn't use that term.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The motivation is that the `<form>` element from HTML 4.0 (which predates cross-site `fetch()` and `XMLHttpRequest`) can submit simple requests to any origin, so anyone writing a server must already be protecting against cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Under this assumption, the server doesn't have to opt-in (by responding to a preflight request) to receive any request that looks like a form submission, since the threat of CSRF is no worse than that of form submission.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] However, the server still must opt-in using `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` to *share* the response with the script.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] No other browsers implement these extra restrictions because they're not part of the spec.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] For example, suppose web content at `https://foo.example` wishes to fetch JSON content from domain `https://bar.other`.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The request header of note is `Origin`, which shows that the invocation is coming from `https://foo.example`.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] In response, the server returns an `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header with `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`, which means that the resource can be accessed by **any** origin.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] This pattern of the `Origin` and `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` headers is the simplest use of the access control protocol.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Unlike *simple requests*, for "preflighted" requests the browser first sends an HTTP request using the `OPTIONS` method to the resource on the other origin, in order to determine if the actual request is safe to send.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Such cross-origin requests are preflighted since they may have implications for user data.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The example above creates an XML body to send with the `POST` request.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Also, a non-standard HTTP `X-PINGOTHER` request header is set.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Such headers are not part of HTTP/1.1, but are generally useful to web applications.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Since the request uses a `Content-Type` of `text/xml`, and since a custom header is set, this request is preflighted.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Let's look at the full exchange between client and server.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The first block above represents the preflight request with the `OPTIONS` method.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The browser determines that it needs to send this based on the request parameters that the JavaScript code snippet above was using, so that the server can respond whether it is acceptable to send the request with the actual request parameters.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] OPTIONS is an HTTP/1.1 method that is used to determine further information from servers, and is a safe method, meaning that it can't be used to change the resource.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The `Access-Control-Request-Method` header notifies the server as part of a preflight request that when the actual request is sent, it will do so with a `POST` request method.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The `Access-Control-Request-Headers` header notifies the server that when the actual request is sent, it will do so with `X-PINGOTHER` and `Content-Type` custom headers.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Now the server has an opportunity to determine whether it can accept a request under these conditions.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The second block above is the response that the server returns, which indicate that the request method (`POST`) and request headers (`X-PINGOTHER`) are acceptable.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The server responds with `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://foo.example`, restricting access to the requesting origin domain only.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] It also responds with `Access-Control-Allow-Methods`, which says that `POST` and `GET` are valid methods to query the resource in question (this header is similar to the `Allow` response header, but used strictly within the context of access control).
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The server also sends `Access-Control-Allow-Headers` with a value of `X-PINGOTHER, Content-Type`, confirming that these are permitted headers to be used with the actual request.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Like `Access-Control-Allow-Methods`, `Access-Control-Allow-Headers` is a comma-separated list of acceptable headers.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Finally, `Access-Control-Max-Age` gives the value in seconds for how long the response to the preflight request can be cached without sending another preflight request.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] In the present case, the max age is 86400 seconds (= 24 hours).
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Note that each browser has a maximum internal value that takes precedence when the `Access-Control-Max-Age` exceeds it.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Not all browsers currently support following redirects after a preflighted request.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The CORS protocol originally required that behavior but was subsequently changed to no longer require it.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] However, not all browsers have implemented the change, and thus still exhibit the originally required behavior.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Make another request (the *real* request) using the URL you obtained from `Response.url` or `XMLHttpRequest.responseURL` in the first step.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] However, if the request is one that triggers a preflight due to the presence of the `Authorization` header in the request, you won't be able to work around the limitation using the steps above.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] And you won't be able to work around it at all unless you have control over the server the request is being made to.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The most interesting capability exposed by both `fetch()` or `XMLHttpRequest` and CORS is the ability to make "credentialed" requests that are aware of HTTP cookies and HTTP Authentication information.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] By default, in cross-origin `fetch()` or `XMLHttpRequest` calls, browsers will *not* send credentials.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] To ask for a `fetch()` request to include credentials, set the `credentials` option to `"include"`.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] To ask for an `XMLHttpRequest` request to include credentials, set the `XMLHttpRequest.withCredentials` property to `true`.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] In this example, content originally loaded from `https://foo.example` makes a GET request to a resource on `https://bar.other` which sets Cookies.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] This code creates a `Request` object, setting the `credentials` option to `"include"` in the constructor, then passes this request into `fetch()`.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Since this is a simple `GET` request, it is not preflighted but the browser will **reject** any response that does not have the `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` header set to `true`, and **not** make the response available to the invoking web content.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] CORS-preflight requests must never include credentials.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The *response* to a preflight request must specify `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true` to indicate that the actual request can be made with credentials.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Firefox 87 allows this non-compliant behavior to be enabled by setting the preference: `network.cors_preflight.allow_client_cert` to `true` (Firefox bug 1511151).
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Chromium-based browsers currently always send TLS client certificates in CORS preflight requests (Chrome bug 775438).
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] If a request includes a credential (most commonly a `Cookie` header) and the response includes an `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` header (that is, with the wildcard), the browser will block access to the response, and report a CORS error in the devtools console.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] But if a request does include a credential (like the `Cookie` header) and the response includes an actual origin rather than the wildcard (like, for example, `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://example.com`), then the browser will allow access to the response from the specified origin.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Also note that any `Set-Cookie` response header in a response would not set a cookie if the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` value in that response is the `*` wildcard rather an actual origin.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Note that cookies set in CORS responses are subject to normal third-party cookie policies.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] In the example above, the page is loaded from `foo.example` but the `Set-Cookie` header in the response is sent by `bar.other`, and would thus not be saved if the user's browser is configured to reject all third-party cookies.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Cookies set in CORS requests and responses are subject to normal third-party cookie policies.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Third-party cookie policies may prevent third party cookies being sent in requests, effectively stopping a site from making credentialed requests even if permitted by the third party server (using `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials`).
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The default policy differs between browsers, but may be set using the SameSite attribute.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Even if credentialed requests are allowed, a browser may be configured to reject all third-party cookies in responses.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] This section lists the HTTP response headers that servers return for access control requests as defined by the Cross-Origin Resource Sharing specification.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The previous section gives an overview of these in action.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` specifies either a single origin which tells browsers to allow that origin to access the resource; or else — for requests **without** credentials — the `*` wildcard tells browsers to allow any origin to access the resource.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The `Access-Control-Expose-Headers` header adds the specified headers to the allowlist that JavaScript (such as `Response.headers`) in browsers is allowed to access.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The `Access-Control-Max-Age` header indicates how long the results of a preflight request can be cached.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] For an example of a preflight request, see the above examples.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The `delta-seconds` parameter indicates the number of seconds the results can be cached.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` header indicates whether or not the response to the request can be exposed when the `credentials` flag is true.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] When used as part of a response to a preflight request, this indicates whether or not the actual request can be made using credentials.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Note that simple `GET` requests are not preflighted, and so if a request is made for a resource with credentials, if this header is not returned with the resource, the response is ignored by the browser and not returned to web content.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Credentialed requests are discussed above.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The `Access-Control-Allow-Methods` header specifies the method or methods allowed when accessing the resource.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] This is used in response to a preflight request.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The conditions under which a request is preflighted are discussed above.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] An example of a preflight request is given above, including an example which sends this header to the browser.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The `Access-Control-Allow-Headers` header is used in response to a preflight request to indicate which HTTP headers can be used when making the actual request.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] This header is the server side response to the browser's `Access-Control-Request-Headers` header.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] This section lists headers that clients may use when issuing HTTP requests in order to make use of the cross-origin sharing feature.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Note that these headers are set for you when making invocations to servers.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Developers making cross-origin requests do not have to set any cross-origin sharing request headers programmatically.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The `Origin` header indicates the origin of the cross-origin access request or preflight request.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The origin is a URL indicating the server from which the request is initiated.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] It does not include any path information, only the server name.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Note that in any access control request, the `Origin` header is **always** sent.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The `Access-Control-Request-Method` is used when issuing a preflight request to let the server know what HTTP method will be used when the actual request is made.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] Examples of this usage can be found above.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] The `Access-Control-Request-Headers` header is used when issuing a preflight request to let the server know what HTTP headers will be used when the actual request is made (for example, by passing them as the `headers` option).
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/guides-cors] This browser-side header will be answered by the complementary server-side header of `Access-Control-Allow-Headers`.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/request-mode] It’s been available across browsers since March 2017.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/request-mode] The **`mode`** read-only property of the `Request` interface contains the mode of the request (e.g., `cors`, `no-cors`, `same-origin`, or `navigate`.) This is used to determine if cross-origin requests lead to valid responses, and which properties of the response are readable.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/request-mode] To construct a request with a specific mode, pass the desired value as the `RequestInit.mode` option to the `Request.Request()` constructor.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/request-mode] Note that setting particular modes, especially `no-cors`, places restrictions on the request methods and headers that may be used, and prevents JavaScript from accessing the response headers or body.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/request-mode] See the documentation for `RequestInit.mode` for more details.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/request-mode] If a request is made to another origin with this mode set, the result is an error.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/request-mode] Disables CORS for cross-origin requests.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/request-mode] The response is *opaque*, meaning that its headers and body are not available to JavaScript.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/request-mode] If the request is cross-origin then it will use the Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) mechanism.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/request-mode] The `navigate` value is intended to be used only by HTML navigation.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/request-mode] A navigate request is created only while navigating between documents.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/request-mode] Requests can be initiated in a variety of ways, and the mode for a request depends on the particular means by which it was initiated.
[src:cross-origin-resource-sharing/request-mode] For example, when a `Request` object is created using the `Request()` constructor, the value of the `mode` property for that `Request` is set to `cors`.
